benchmark_config.jira_title: Implement/Test API: GET /1.0/kb/accounts/{accountId}/emails/{accountEmailId}/auditLogsWithHistory - Retrieve account email audit logs with history by id

covered: Valid Request: TC01 verifies successful retrieval with 200 and content-type application/json and key fields for AuditLog objects.
Empty Response: TC02 covers the case where an existing resource has no audit logs and expects an empty JSON array with 200.
Resource-not-found error handling: TC03, TC04, TC18, TC19 test 404 responses for missing account and/or accountEmail resources and empty DB states.
Input validation: TC05, TC06 and the security tests TC13/TC14 cover invalid UUID/format and injection/XSS attempts yielding 400s.
Authentication/Authorization negative cases: TC07 and TC08 cover missing and invalid authentication producing 401s.
Robustness / resilience: TC09 (503) and TC12 (504) cover service unavailable and downstream timeout behavior.
Large-data handling (basic): TC11 asserts behavior with a very large number of audit logs and includes a response time expectation.
Response correctness: TC15 and TC16 address ordering and schema regression/backward-compatibility concerns.
Query parameter tolerance: TC10 verifies the endpoint ignores or tolerates extra query parameters.
gaps: Pagination: No test asserts pagination behavior (limit/offset/page headers, next links, or partial payload responses). TC11 checks large payload size but not paginated responses or limits.
Caching Behavior: No tests check caching-related headers (ETag, Last-Modified, Cache-Control) or conditional GET semantics (If-None-Match / 304 responses).
Rate Limiting / Throttling: No scenarios exercise rate limiting (429) or burst behavior under many rapid requests.
Authorization - Forbidden (403): There are tests for missing/invalid auth (401) but not for valid auth with insufficient privileges (403) if the product differentiates these cases.
Positive content details: While fields are checked at high level, there is no detailed validation of AuditLog field types/values (e.g., changeDate format, id UUID pattern, history structure content).
Error body structure: Error responses are asserted by message text only; tests do not validate standard error schema/fields (error code, type, details) nor consistent content-type for errors.
Caching/conditional updates for resource history: No tests for evolution of history across multiple calls (e.g., ETag changes after updates).
Pagination performance/streaming: Large dataset test includes a response time check but does not validate memory/streaming behavior or partial responses for extremely large sets.
recommendations: Add explicit pagination tests: verify limit/offset (or page & size) parameters, correct counts, next/prev links or headers, and consistent ordering across pages. Include tests for requesting out-of-range pages returning an empty array or appropriate metadata.
Add caching/conditional request tests: verify ETag and Cache-Control headers on 200 responses; test If-None-Match resulting in 304 and confirm ETag changes after a resource update.
Add rate-limiting tests: simulate rapid repeated requests to assert 429 responses and appropriate Retry-After header behavior if rate limits apply.
Include authorization role tests: add scenarios where an authenticated user lacks permission to access the account/email and assert 403 Forbidden and correct error body.

Strengthen schema checks: validate types and formats for AuditLog fields (UUID pattern for id, ISO8601 for changeDate, non-empty history array shape) and ensure error responses follow a standard error schema.
Add tests for error content-type and structured error fields so clients can reliably parse errors.
Expand large-data tests to include pagination + performance under paging and memory usage boundaries; include streaming or chunked response validation if applicable.
Add regression tests around ETag/conditional behavior to ensure clients can cache results safely and detect changes to history.
